üìã Usage:
Installation and Execution

# Make the script executable
chmod +x kernel_cleaner.py

# Check the status of installed kernels (no root privileges needed)
python3 kernel_cleaner.py --status

# Simulate removal (see what would be deleted)
python3 kernel_cleaner.py --dry-run

# Perform actual cleanup (requires sudo)
sudo python3 kernel_cleaner.py

# Verbose mode
sudo python3 kernel_cleaner.py --verbose

Available Options

    -s, --status : Show the status of installed kernels

    -n, --dry-run : Simulate cleanup without deleting anything

    -v, --verbose : Verbose mode for more detailed output

üõ°Ô∏è Built-in Safeguards

    Current kernel protection: Prevents removal of the running kernel

    Backup kernel: Ensures at least one alternate kernel is retained

    Confirmation prompt: Asks for confirmation before deleting anything

    Privilege check: Verifies root permissions when required

    GRUB update: Automatically updates the bootloader after changes

üîç Example Usage

# First, check current kernel status
python3 kernel_cleaner.py --status

# Then, simulate what would be removed
python3 kernel_cleaner.py --dry-run

# Finally, run the actual cleanup
sudo python3 kernel_cleaner.py

